,Recommended,293780,31109901,Posted: 12 April,all,Sir Pencil,"Crawl is an excellent couch co-op game which encourages you to work together as a team to end the hero's life, then take their place and fight your way to salvation by besting the cthulhian horror that resides at the end of it all... or die and have your humanity stolen, only to be cursed to rot forever amidst your wrath in the infinite tombs of Crawl.Crawl hits all the right notes:Monsters scale well over time, going from murderous nuisances to outright tough-as-nails murderbeastsHero weapons and abilities are interesting and variedBuffs and debuffs provide an additional strategic layer which raises the game from simply ""good"" to ""great""There's a heavy cyber-lovecraftian theme which elevates the mood. It's immersive and tense, appealing to that intrinsic desire to survive which exists within every human.I love the fact that your scorecard is saved between runs. I also laughed out loud when the game told me that my hero had been ""lost forever"" because we ran out of attempts against the boss (and then it deleted my scorecard, a really nice touch).I never felt like any of my deaths were unfair, or that any of the monsters in particular didn't come with their own weakness to exploit. Your decisions really shape your hero and you'd do well to expect your enemies to exploit gaps in your defense.It doesn't have online multi-player, but that's a small concession for what is such a tight and cohesive array of elements that come together and create an experience that'll have you sweating from the sheer intensity. Even if you don't have enough people nearby who can slum it on your couch to gather up 4 players, Crawl provides a powerful AI that will keep you on your toes. I especially thought it was a nice touch when the AI even goes through the human motions in shops and goes through upgrade menus like a regular player - its an oddly salient touch that I didn't know I wanted until I saw it."
