,Recommended,293780,11605044,"Posted: 8 August, 2014",all,Kirbyxox,"Never before have I felt that a game truly defined a brawler co-op+VS experience until crawl.Games such as castle crashers and even the old final fights had somesort of co-op and some some sort of vs but traversing the level feltexactly the same as if you were doing it single player with a tinytaste of competitive on the side. Crawl doesn't do this, playing alongsideyour friends means having to keep an eye on every single thing eachof your friends does. Their level, their money, who's hanging back tojump in and steal the kill, who's flinging an all out assault. It'sextremely enthralling and keeps you on your toes throughout eachand every game, you even start to get some of, what I like to call,the mario party aspect. You start resenting and shouting at yourfriends. ""WHY DID YOU HAVE TO FIGHT THE BOSS, IT'S OUR LAST TRY!?""""DAMMIT I WAS GONNA BUY THAT WEAPON!"" etc, etc.Crawl is a great game not only in multiplayer with your friendsbut even in single player, with advanced and clever AI thatseem to know what you'll try before you try it (although theydo get caught on boxes sometimes) making even single playerquests an exciting experience.I've been playing on off since release and even I still haven'tunlocked everything which means there is a lot in this game toobtain and because it's still being built even MORE will be added.I hope you consider Crawl as the multiplayer experience of the yearand buy yourself something fun and exciting.With some frogs, demons and just a dash of Lovecraftian horrorCrawl is a great game that deserves your time."
,Recommended,293780,11605219,"Posted: 8 August, 2014",all,sevrl bats,"Get it! Go! Now! Take it! Have it! Love it!Crawl's a short-session action roguelike. It takes thirty minutes or so to play a single round, and win or lose, you'll net new unlocks to change up future crawls. Fast-paced and capable of hammering home a gloriously tooth-grinding need to win, even just against the AI bots, Crawl is exactly what it looked like in that first video that took us all by storm months ago (and if you haven't seen that, watch it at once, it's on this very page).Most impressive is the game's catchup mechanics. Each player has three tracks of monsters that they level up from lowly worms into terrible dragons, from cackling skeletons into...whatever that giant goddamn black knight thing is, seriously, he's worryingly huge. The ""Vitae"" these upgrades require is earned when your -opponents- level up. That's right: The further ahead one player's human shape gets, the nastier the beasts he'll find himself facing, and those who've been struggling will have the most worrying monsters of all. I was a little unclear on how the game decided what tier to spawn you at, but it seems to have a similar catchup mentality (I saw an AI who was wayyy behind the rest of us spawn as a top-tier dragon twice in a row).It does a lot to keep the humanity ball passing around. After reaching level ten (which is not the cap, if there is one), that player, when human, can use one of the portals scattered around the dungeon to take on the boss. If he loses, he's ejected, but gets to stay human (if a human at terrifyingly low life). The game can't drag on forever, though: The third time the boss is engaged (by any player) the portal explodes in a totally metal portal explosion. Defeat of the human player now means the end of the game, a consolation prize for the ghosts and absolute devouring of the foolish human who'd tested his might and failed.It all comes together really well. The joyful rage of getting your killing blows on the human stolen by an UNWORTHY GHOSTLY ALLY who hadn't contributed much is palpable, and the satisfaction at pulling apart the creatures as a human and getting your big, glitzy retro levelup effects is real. Both modes of play are fun, which is probably the key factor here--dying sucks, but hey, on the other hand, now you get to be a giant ♥♥♥♥off black knight and make your friends bleed. And that blood spilled when playing as a monster gets saved up, to be converted into gold when you next find yourself human. There's never a lazy moment: It's constantly important that you be pummeling your friends (or computers).There's an almost infinite amount that could be done with this game. Items could be added forever. Alternate bosses, more sets of monsters to pick from, hideous new traps, diversified level pallettes--the paging space is almost numbing. So buy this game! Encourage our antipodean friends to make more out of it!"
