,Recommended,293780,14166453,"Posted: 25 January, 2015",all,TheMightyJohnFu,"Review Written on 25/01/2015 (Subject to change) Scroll for Pro's,Cons and Summary.Do you cherish your relationship with your friends?THEN DO NOT BUY THIS GAME!Crawl was made  with the intentions of turning even the strongest of bonds in to heated rivalries; One moment you will find yourself working with others to lower the heroes health, the next you're viciously scrambling to ensure you are the one who delivers  the final blow to take his place.Crawl offers that which seems to be a rareity in modern games: 4 player local multiplayer. Bringing back the golden days of real couch co-op. The game practically comes gift-wrapped in nostalgia, with its retro-arcade visuals,8-bit audio, two-button combat system and fast-paced gameplay.Gameplay:To begin with, you are greeted with an ""Insert coin screen"" where you must create a character name consisting of three letters. As simple as it sounds, it immediately welcomes you.Players  must then  select a god to worhsip. Each offering three different monsters with their own evolution path and starting conditions.The premise is simple; One player starts as the hero, who must reach level 10 by descending floors to defeat the boss and claim salvation.Sounds easy eh?This would be the case, if you didn't have three other players , in ghost form, competing to become the hero in the process, by possessing traps, summoning monsters and deploying slimes. This makes survival as the hero extremely difficult, even more so as the other players gain ""Vitae"" a currency used to evolve their monsters each time the hero levels up or they draw blood from him.Fear not though! All is not lost, as each floor contains a blacksmith, where the Hero is able to spend gold they have accumilated through killing monsters, to purchase new weapons, trinkets and powers . However, getting to the shop first on each floor is essential if you want to claim all the best gear before anyone else.This is where Crawl really shines, it offers a sense of progression. The amount of purchaseable gear is satisfactory, and even after death, any itmes purchased are not lost.  The monsters don't lose out either, as between floors, players are prompted to evolve their monsters, becoming stronger and increasing their chances of killing the hero.Now, let's discuss one of my favourite aspects of the game:Bosses.Once players have reached level 10, they are able to face a boss, should they choose to do so, by entering the boss room and standing on a glyph. However, you can only have one attempt at the boss per floor, and three overall between everyone. This is when things become interesting, as you need to ensure you are well equipped for the battle, but have to accept the fact that persuing better gear always comes with the risk of dying and not becoming the hero again, allowing others to face the boss.Here's the brilliant part; Once the boss fight begins, any player who is not the hero is able to possess one of the bosses body parts such as the arms and head. Each limb will have a different attack, meaning cooperation and coordination is essential.If the hero prevails, the player wins the game, If the hero is to fail, he will be sent back to the floor with little health and the game continues. If all boss attempts have been used and the hero dies on the final attempt, it's game over. The winner being decided by whoever has accumilated the most XP during the game...Oh and the hero's character is permanently lost, although there seems to be no real penalty for this as there is nothing tying you to your character post-game. You can literally create another character with the same name straight after. To counter this, me and my buddies came up with a system where if your character dies, you can no longer use that three letter name again. Not much of a loss, but better than what the system currently offers.With the completion of each game, win or fail, you earn unlocks. Wether it be new traps, new evolutions for your monsters, weapons , tomes etc.... This adds to the games already enormous amount of replayability. (After 15 hours of play I still haven't unlocked everything!)Mechanics:The game plays best with a controller, although a mouse and keyboard is entirely useable. The two-button system is easy to use; you have a primary and secondary attack and a stick for movement, although the mouse can also used for movement; your character will move to where the cursor is pointed. I found the mouse a little more tedious and difficult to use as opposed to the gamepad.The fighting system is easy to understand, the difficulty comes from avoiding attacks and timing.  Personally, I'd like to be able to carry a ranged and a melee weapon and have another button to switch between the two.All in all, due to the simplicity of the controls, combat feels fluent and tight, with the animations complimenting and completing the system.Multiplayer:Be prepared for cursing, shouting, physical violence and possibly a heart attack-enduced death as you work extremely hard to bring the heroes health down only to have a friend steal the kill and become the hero.This game is best experienced with friends. You can of course play solo, the A.I is more than capable of providing a decent challenge, and is surpringly believeable, making human-like errors. But local couch multiplayer is the heart and soul of this game, and besides, there's no better feeling than defeating your friends and claiming salvation.Unfortunately, at the time of this review, Online multiplayer is not currently implemented. This is a shame because me and my buddies aren't always together, and we'd love to get some Crawl on when this is the case. Fingers crossed though!Another feature I would love to see in this game is Steam Workshop intergration. I'm sure modders would have a blast creating massive amounts of content. This would no doubt increase the lifespan of Crawl.Graphics and audio:Crawl is certainly a pretty game. From the intentional graphical glitches at the main menu, to the colourful displays of attacks ,traps, monsters and blood spills. The pixelated aesthetics feel right at home and sit comfortably amongst the haunting 8-bit track that accompanies them. The randomly generted dungeons  can get a little samey, but there is enough diversity to keep things interesting and the developers have confirmed that dungeon generation, music,  monsters, traps, items and a whole plethora of content will be added.IssuesNaturally, being in early access, Crawl is not without it's flaws; Ghosts being dragged too quickly from the last room into the next when the hero is running through them, sometimes resulting in the inability to utilise a room filled with traps. The occasional door refusing to let you pass or objects disappearing and reappearing. But these are problems that can easily be ironed out; over the 15 hours I've played, I had only encountered a few of these issues and rarely did they hinder the experience.Pro's:-4 playerLocal multiplayer-Progression system/RPG Elements-Brilliant premise; friends play as monsters-Fast-paced gameplay-Lot's of content-Replayiblity-Feels polished-Easy to jump straight in-Gorgeous pixel art-Strong mechanics-Low system requirements-More content to comeCons:-No Steam Workshop-No online Multiplayer-You will put Friendships to the test-Occasional bugsSummary:Crawl feels incredibly well-polished for an early access game, offering fast-paced gameplay, a unique take on the genre and a level of competitiveness that could only be achieved within it's own universe.8.5/10  ""Must Buy"""
