,Recommended,293780,23500728,"Posted: 11 June, 2016",all,Ethnographix,"CHECK OUT THE WHOLE REVIEW AT ETHNOGRAPHIX:NOTHING BUT GAMING CULTURE AND KATS!All games have a realm they are best suited to. Mass Effect is an excellent single-player example, Populous is one of the best God games out there; FTL, the standard for roguelikes. So when it comes to multiplayer games that are not only fun, challenging, and fresh but that allow you to drop a hot mess on your buddy's head, no game is better suited than Crawl.But how to best describe a game that effortlessly packs together arcade style multiplayer alongside RPG friendly player progression and item usage? Well if I had to use a single word to do so, I'd say something along the lines of...bananas.This game is ♥♥♥♥ing bananas.First off, the premise. You and up to four other players (bots are also an option) are tasked with defeating the final boss in a dungeon crawler style series of levels that contain all manner of hazards from fire-spewing torches to Zelda style porcupine bricks that careen from one side of the map to the next. At any given moment, one player is the human in search of the end of the dungeon while the rest are either floating apparitions that collect globs of ectoplasmic goo to use as a weapon later on or to possess vile aberrations; each of which possess' it's own unique approach to dispatching the lone human paragon.Monster progression is tiered and each tree provides a different approach and selection of satanic beasts you will be able to choose from. This includes, but is not limited to, Cthulhu (+3 Lovecraft boner), Skeletor's misogynistic cousin, and a barfing carp or, as I have come to know it as, ""Barfamander.""Yup, it's sort of like Army of Darkness got drunk and had a sloppy ♥♥♥♥ with a desperate Pokemon.You'll spend a great deal of time possessing traps as you chisel away at the human in play in the hopes that, by killing them in a Shogun Assassin style arterial splash of blood, you will land the final blow and thus become the human until the same fate befalls you. It's a fun give-and-take that means that anyone can end up being the winner regardless of points or skill level (although the latter certainly factors in).Fun Steam based additions have been somewhat regular and made the title a real gem as far as replay and for the creepily glitched out visuals and sound that operate like an NES on meth. Got a few bucks to spare with the buddies you love to hate most?Get your Crawl on.CHECK OUT THE WHOLE REVIEW AT ETHNOGRAPHIX:NOTHING BUT GAMING CULTURE AND KATS!"
